pageSummary: We are staying silent to raise money for Macmillan because we wanted to do something to help others
pageSummaryWhat: We are staying silent to raise money for Macmillan
pageSummaryWhy: we wanted to do something to help others
story:
Thanks for supporting Bethan and Hannah with their sponsored silence in aid of Macmillan Cancer Support. 

We know far too many people whose lives have been touched by cancer, especially our Uncle Martin. He is so much fun and we love him so very much and whilst we can not get to see him much we wanted to show him how special he is. 

Keeping quiet is super tricky for us but we wanted to do something hard to show how much we care. 

The girls started their sponsored silence this morning at 8.30am and have just gone to bed. They have written notes and used sign language all day to communicate with us...mainly requests for snacks to be honest! We are really really proud of them and hope they will raise lots of money. 

Macmillan is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

pageSummary: Running 100 miles in November because Our family has been affected
story:
After completing Cash for kids 5k a day I set myself another challenge so signed up to run 100 miles in the month of November, to keep me motivated and give back to an amazing charity which is very close to both Steve’s and my family’s hearts, Felt it was fitting to run for Macmillan Cancer as November is Ronnie’s (my father in law) birthday month, he would of been 73 years old. He is missed every day by all his family and friends ,from his very bad jokes and his moans about pretty much most things in life 🙈but we’d give anything to hear those bad jokes and moans again

pageSummary: Walking 50 miles with Pacey because This year, I haven't been able to walk one mile
pageSummaryWhy: This year, I haven't been able to walk one mile
story:
Through injury to my foot and ankle, I've spent most of this year in a compression boot.

Walking has been a massive obstacle for me as I can't even walk a mile, let alone 50!


The past few weeks I've been trying to increase my distance but the aftermath has been unbearable. And it's been impacting my mental health.

So I need to get out there and strengthen this foot....so with Paceys help we have signed up to walk 50 miles over November and are hoping to raise some dolla for charity.


So please donate, even if its 1p....as i was taught in my first job, every little helps.
title: Rhiannon's Walking 50 miles

pageSummary: Sadly on 27th October we lost our wonderful Dad <U+0001F499> because Dad was very thankful of all the help he received.
pageSummaryWhat: Sadly on 27th October we lost our wonderful Dad <U+0001F499>
pageSummaryWhy: Dad was very thankful of all the help he received.
story:
We lost our wonderful Dad/Husband on 27th October, to cancer.He tried as best he could and fought so hard, always remaining positive and still maintained his fun loving personality through out. He couldn’t bear the thought of others young and old going through what he had and wanted to help others. We would like to raise £73 a £1 for each year of his wonderful life and to try and stop this awful disease  💙

Fay, Marie and Sylvia 💕

story:
Thanks for visiting my page.

With the UK going into a second lockdown I have decided to give up alcohol indefinitely as there is nowhere to go and no one we can see, our wellbeing during this horrid time is so important and I feel the British Heart Foundation is the right charity to back as their research goes far beyond the heart.

I will be looking to raise funds through November 2020 by giving up drink, some may think this task is too easy to warrant a donation so as well as going alcohol free I will also be growing my beard out, I'm starting at a 2 and a half weeks worth of growth already so another month on top will be interesting and if we reach my goal of £500 donated I will continue the growth into December and for the last day of work before Christmas break, as before, I will dye my beard the colour of choice as voted by those who donate to this cause. Thank you in advance ppl!

Each row will be verified by upload to the Concept 2 global log book for 2021 Season :

pageSummary: I’m running 5k every day of November because it’s 5 years this month since mum passed away.
pageSummaryWhat: I’m running 5k every day of November
pageSummaryWhy: it’s 5 years this month since mum passed away.
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. 

Mum passed away 5 years ago from Heart Failure. My family and our friends all miss her dearly, but we remember the good times, the laughs, her kindness and her love for all those around her. She worked hard to support 4 young children after Dad passed away, never once complaining. She was always proud of her appearance, immaculately dressed for all occasions, loved a G n T, and shared her Fries Five Centres with us as a treat on a weekend.! She cooked the best Sunday Roast, and Christmas Dinner was amazing, never to beaten, except for the prawn cocktail in some sort of weird cocktail type glass (‘cos we was dead posh!). 

So, I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. I’m attempting to run 5k everyday of November, so 150k in total. Come wind or rain, sun or storms, aching muscles or blistered feet - the plan is to be out there every day. 

Why a target of £750, simply because it’s 5 years and 5 times my total distance. £5 for every kilometre.....gotta be worth it.!

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge weve faced in our 60 year history. And its led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, weve never needed people like you more.

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into groundbreaking science and support for the people who need us most. Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the worlds biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we cant drop the ball now.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Sadly my gran passed away on 21/10/2020 after a short and sudden illness. In memory of my gran I would like to raise money for a charity very close to her heart.

Since we cannot take any cash donations due to Covid-19 restrictions I thought a just giving page would be more practical for the time being.

pageSummaryWhat: He is giving up his favourite crisps for a month!
story:
Jasper wanted to raise some money charity. We had a chat and decided the best way to do that right now is to give something up.  There were a few suggestions but most of them wouldn't have been hard for him, which is how we decided on him giving up his favourite crisps.  

Jasper eats a pack of McCoys flame grilled steak crisps (and only these crisps!) Every single day, without fail. He loves them and looks forward to this treat so its going to be hard for him not to have them for the whole of November! 


And just for good measure, he is banned for eating any crisps whilst this challenge is on! 

Jasper chose to support GOSH as he had both his surgeries there & they will do the others he will need until he is an adult. They are an amazing hospital providing world class care, but a very personal service, with love, kindness and compassion not just to the children receiving care but to their parents and family. 

Jasper would not be able to walk, run, climb, dance or love an active life had it not been for the surgeries he received at GOSH so it is a place very close to his (and his families) heart.

Jasper understands this is a tough time to be asking for donations, but he would be very grateful for anything at all that you can donate, to allow him to reach his target.

Thank you.

pageSummaryWhat: I am raisIng much needed funds
pageSummaryWhy: They give children and families hope, care & life
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

This year, due to Covid-19, Great Ormond St Hospital (GOSH) predicts with most of their major fundraising activities cancelled, they will suffer a drop of as much as £25 million in income that supports the hospital! 

This got me thinking... charity events are cancelled and I think it’s fair to assume so are Work /friends Christmas Parties!  (No need for a new outfit or paying for a turkey dinner!) 

So maybe for those of us fortunate enough to be financially coping in these difficult times, a donation from our Christmas party pot could help GOSH! 

As parents of a child who’s life has been transformed by GOSH, Matt and I, will feel forever grateful and in the hospitals debt! 

As a parent, GOSH is the last place in the world you want to take your own child; that first ever visit is tough and your eyes are opened to a world you never really knew existed! But once you overcome the fact your child needs GOSH then it is simply the most outstanding, phenomenal place. The talent of the care teams and their passion to constantly research and advance their skills to support children like Freya makes us so grateful to live where we do and to Benefit from GOSH. 

Any donation you can give to this amazing NHS children’s Hospital will make a difference! 

In return I am setting myself a personal challenge that through out November I will run 60km. I am rubbish at running and have no idea why people think it’s fun, but that said... it is amazing for the mind and all I have to do is think of the resilience of the children, including Freya, who undergo major treatment at GOSH and I realise the least I can do is drag myself out for a run!

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Cancer Research, Needs us now RIGHT NOW!!! 9.6 Million people die from Cancer each year! This is too many people In the Uk over 165,000 cancer deaths happen annually! #fightcancer #100kburpeechallenge


We are all going through shifting seasons, then COVID 19 disrupted progress for us all, during the peak of the first lockdown you may have found yourself depressed because of the set backs and adversity caused by the virus, now imagine you are a cancer patient with all that stress and the impending fear of what could happen next! Or imagine you was so scared you didn’t go for that scan or check up because you didn’t have good clear advice about what cancer may look like, the advice which could have saved your life if addressed early on!


Cancer services need to remain open and Cancer Research is forever improving because of its importance for future generations, but valuable funding is needed to undertake more research and make breakthroughs and we will get over this adversity together only when we work together towards one goal, that’s when I decided to create a challenge, a challenge to fight poor health, it’s time to make a better future for the next generations and lead by example!


Within us all is a rich capacity, and some of us never get to reach that potential because they are taken away from us far far too early!
“A Journey of Thousand miles begins with a single step - Lao Tzu”

So a journey of 100k burpees begins with a single burpee, so here we go...
Burpee 1/100,000 Burpees


Www.justgiving.com/fundraising/100k-Burpees


#firststeps #challenge #burpees #fundraiser #charityfundraiser #decidetowin #takingownership
#cancerresearch #cancerresearchuk


This is my first ever solo fundraiser, I have set no time limit to complete my burpees by as I have never done any type of challenge on this scale, this is a mountain of a challenge for me someone who eats unhealthy and is overweight but I will be recording all my progress and aim to complete as soon as possible to help Cancer Research get the funding it needs!


Also every pound donated I will match up-to the first £1000*, adding a maximum of £1000 to the end figure if donations exceed the goal.

story:
Since 2013 we have been gathering in increasingly large numbers to play games and raise money for Cancer Research UK on an annual basis.

This year we should have been holding two events, one in Spring and one in November, but with 2020 being as it has both of those events were not able to go ahead.

So we will be using the final two months of the year to host a number of online events encouraging the community to play games together, have some fun, and donate some money to Cancer Research UK.

Spend an evening playing games? Donate the cost of a few beers to the total. Take part in an organised tournament? Donate the cost of entry you would usually expect to the total.

We may not be able to meet in person but we can still play games together and continue to raise life-saving funds for this amazing cause.

story:
2020 has been a year of highs and lows for everyone, espically for those who have been diagnosed or are living with cancer. I have witnessed admiral strength first hand of family and friends who have been diagnosed, are fighting or have sadly lost a loved to this horrible disease.

pageSummary: I am running 70 miles over the month of November because my Mum was supported by Marie Curie at home.
pageSummaryWhat: I am running 70 miles over the month of November
pageSummaryWhy: my Mum was supported by Marie Curie at home.
story:
Hi!

The photo on this page is my Mum on Jack's 1st birthday, it's the only one she really celebrated with him. She died not long after his 2nd. Most people will know he's now 13, so she's been gone a while. Her birthday is 4th November and this year she would have been 70, so I decided I'd like to do something to acknowledge it and see if I could raise a bit of money for the charity that supported us the night before the died. 

Marie Curie were able to send in a nurse overnight to support her and my dad and it made a huge difference so I'm trying to raise at least £200 (which is what it costs for 1 nurse overnight) to ensure they can continue to support other families.

I'm going to be running 70 miles over the month of November which will be a challenge now its much darker and we're about to go into lockdown again, so please, if you can click on the button to donate.

Many Thanks,

Nicola

pageSummary: We can't go to the ball but please give generously because it's a great cause!
pageSummaryWhat: We can't go to the ball but please give generously
story:
My dear mum, Elsa Taylor, organises a ball every November to raise money for Marie Curie, the incredible charity she nursed with for over 30 years.

Around this time of year she’s usually frantic and lost in a whirlwind of tickets, raffle prizes, Champagne bubbles and guest lists.

This year, sadly, none of this is possible. Or, at least, that’s what my Mum thinks. Whilst we might not be able to meet together at Crathorne Hall for a ball we would like to surprise my Mum with a donation to Marie Curie and a fun virtual event on Friday 20 November 2020.  We will announce our grand total to Mum's surprise and play Heads and Tails for your chance to win a bottle of Champagne.  Please send me a message for the event link.

It's a difficult time for everyone as we are enduring another national lockdown, but the work of Marie Curie and their fantastic staff carries on regardless. Marie Curie nurses, like my Mum, work on the front line, night and day, in people’s homes across the UK, providing hands-on care and vital emotional support.

Marie Curie's nine hospices offer the reassurance of specialist care and support, in a friendly, welcoming environment, for people living with a terminal illness and their loved ones around the UK.

Please give what you can.

And remember, not a word to Elsa - or should I say, “Mum’s the word”!

pageSummary: I am climbing Kilimanjaro from the 27th Dec 2020 because it is a charity which is close to my family!
pageSummaryWhat: I am climbing Kilimanjaro from the 27th Dec 2020
pageSummaryWhy: it is a charity which is close to my family!
story:
From the 27th December 2020, I will be climbing up Kilimanjaro in aid of Southend RNLI! 

This is a charity which is close to me, as my grandad was a massive supporter of the RNLI and my brother is a Helm/Crew at the Southend on Sea Station. Seeing him run out in the middle of the night, or on Christmas Day is a sign of the fantastic work the volunteer crew do at Southend. With a crew of over 35, they are one of the busiest coastal stations in the UK - already hitting over 150 jobs for 2020! Not one of crew gets paid at Southend, every single one volunteer their time and effort with the aim of saving lives at sea!

All donations raised are to be utilised at the Southend RNLI Station.

As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place. Thank you.
title: Taking on Kilimanjaro for Southend RNLI!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
image.caption: NA
media.images.image.caption: NA
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
